<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910605-0114</DOCNO><DOCID>910605-0114.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- Communications Transmission:   Company Fails to Make   Payment on Two Loans</HL><DATE>06/05/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   CTIA</CO><MS>TECHNOLOGY (TEC)</MS><IN>COMMUNICATIONS TECHNOLOGY (CMT)</IN><RE>NORTH AMERICA (NME)TEXAS (TX)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   Communications Transmission Inc. said it is in default onits loan obligations because it failed to pay $15 million of$35 million due yesterday.   By failing to make the payment Communications Transmissionalso is in default on subordinated debt agreements, certainequipment leases and loan agreements of its ALCCommunications Corp. subsidiary.</LP><TEXT>   Communications Transmission said its $125 million seniorloan is held by five banks led by NCNB Corp., based inCharlotte, N.C. The company added that its $103 million insubordinated debt is owed to Prudential Insurance Co. ofAmerica.   Communications Transmission, based in Austin, Texas,restructured its debt last year. The company said it istrying to negotiate new terms with its senior lenders andequipment lessors.   For the first quarter, the operator of microwave andfiber-optic communications networks posted a loss of $13million, or $1.32 a share, compared with a loss in theyear-earlier period of $8.7 million, or 91 cents a share.Revenue was flat at about $98 million.</TEXT></DOC>